  "prompt": "Is there a consensus that money laundering is against the law?",
  "response": "Yes, there is a global consensus that money laundering is against the law.\n\nHere's why:\n\n*   **International Treaties and Conventions:** The United Nations Convention Against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988) and the United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000) were pivotal in criminalizing money laundering internationally. Many other regional and international agreements further solidify this stance.\n*   **National Laws:** Virtually every country has enacted laws criminalizing money laundering. These laws often vary in detail but share the fundamental goal of preventing the concealment of illegally obtained funds.\n*   **Financial Action Task Force (FATF):** The FATF is an inter-governmental body that sets international standards to combat money laundering, terrorist financing, and other related threats to the integrity of the international financial system. Its recommendations are widely adopted by countries worldwide.\n*   **Purpose:** The very purpose of criminalizing money laundering is to deter and punish those who attempt to disguise the origins of illicit funds, thereby weakening criminal enterprises and protecting the financial system.\n*   **No Legitimate Argument for Legality:** There is no legitimate legal or ethical argument to support the idea that money laundering should be legal. It is inherently linked to and facilitates criminal activity.\n\nTherefore, there is no debate within the legal or ethical community about the illegality of money laundering. It is universally recognized as a crime.",
